# Gupshup Partner Portal Integration Rulebook

Reference for building against the **Gupshup Partner Portal** (WhatsApp Business API BSP). Use this before writing any Gupshup client code. Source: [partner-docs.gupshup.io](https://partner-docs.gupshup.io/docs/gupshup-partner-eco-system) · full index at [`/llms.txt`](https://partner-docs.gupshup.io/llms.txt).

> This CRM sends WhatsApp via **Gupshup Partner Portal** (primary) with **MSG91** fallback for transactional messages. Meta Cloud API was removed; when adding provider code, mirror the existing pipeline (`send-whatsapp.js`: dedupe → persist → provider → wallet debit) and register it in `whatsapp-router.js`; do **not** bypass that pipeline.

## 1. Model & base URL

- Gupshup is a **BSP / Meta Tech Provider**. Partners are ISVs/TPs; the Partner Portal manages many customers' **WABA apps**. WhatsApp is the **only** channel; bot studio / journey builder are NOT available to partners.
- Billing is **prepaid** (partner wallet is debited per customer usage; commissions apply).
- **Base URL:** `https://partner.gupshup.io` — all partner APIs live under `/partner/...`.
- Store the base URL as `GUPSHUP_PARTNER_BASE_URL` (default `https://partner.gupshup.io`); never hardcode inline.

## 2. Three credentials — do not confuse them

| Credential | How obtained | Scope | Lifetime | Header usage |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Client Secret** | Generated in Portal → Settings → API client details | Identifies partner user | Recommend ≤ 3 months (rotate) | Passed as `secret`/`password` to login API only |
| **Partner Token** (JWT) | `POST /partner/account/login` with `email` + `secret` | All partner-account APIs | **24 hours** | `Authorization: <PARTNER_TOKEN>` |
| **App Access Token** | `GET /partner/app/{appId}/token` (needs Partner Token) | One WABA app: messages, templates, subscriptions, media | Idempotent; long-lived (`expiresOn: 0` = no expiry) | `Authorization: <PARTNER_APP_TOKEN>` |

- The **Client Secret** is the login password (post 20-Nov-2024). Older accounts may still use their portal password until they rotate.
- `GET .../token` is **idempotent**: returns the existing token if present, else generates one. Cache it; do not call it per-message (rate limit: 10/min/app).

## 3. Token lifecycle (MANDATORY caching)

```
login (email+secret) ──> Partner Token (24h)  ──cache──> reuse until ~23h
                              │
                              └─> GET /app/{appId}/token ──> App Token ──cache──> reuse
```

- **Cache the Partner Token** (~24h) and **App Token** (per `appId`) in DB/Redis. Refresh Partner Token *before* expiry with a small skew (e.g. renew at 23h).
- On `401`/`403` from any app API, refresh the App Token once, then the Partner Token, then retry once. Do not loop.
- **Never** log or return tokens/secrets. Encrypt at rest with the existing `lib/crypto.js` (`encrypt`/`decrypt`), same as `WhatsAppAccount.accessTokenCipher`.
- Login rate limit is **10/min** — a token-refresh stampede will get you `429`.

## 4. Rate limits (enforce client-side)

| Endpoint | Limit |
|---|---|
| `/partner/account/login` | 10 / min |
| `/partner/app/{appId}/token` | 10 / min / app |
| `/partner/app/{appId}/health` | 10 / min / app |
| `/partner/app/{appId}/templates` | 10 / min / app |
| `/partner/app/{appId}/template/analytics` | 10 / 60s / app |
| `/partner/app/{appId}/subscription` | 5 / 60s / app |
| `/partner/app/{appId}/media/` | 10 / sec / app |
| `/partner/app/{appId}/mmlite/msg/enable` | 2 / hour / app |
| **All others** | **10 / sec** |

- Cooldown = the window unit (1s for per-second, 1min for per-minute).
- Treat `429 {"status":"error","message":"Too Many Requests"}` with exponential backoff + jitter. Prefer caching/queueing over retries.

## 5. Core endpoints

**Account (Partner Token):**
- `POST /partner/account/login` → `{ token, id, billingType, ... }` (form-urlencoded: `email`, `secret`).
- `GET  /partner/account/api/partnerApps` → list of linked apps (`id`, `name`, `live`, `healthy`, `cap`, ...).
- `POST /partner/account/api/appLink` → link an existing Gupshup app (API key + app name) to the partner.
- `GET  /partner/app/{appId}/token` → App Access Token.

**App (App Token) — messaging & management:**
- `POST /partner/app/{appId}/v3/message` → send session (free-form) messages (see §6).
- `POST /partner/app/{appId}/template/msg` → send **template** message by template ID (see §6).
- `POST /partner/app/{appId}/templates` → apply for a template (with sample media / `handleId`).
- `GET  /partner/app/{appId}/templates` → list templates (+ rejection reason, `correctCategory`).
- `POST /partner/app/{appId}/subscription` → set webhook subscription (see §7).
- `POST /partner/app/{appId}/media` (file) / `.../media?url=` (URL) → upload → media ID.
- `GET  /partner/app/{appId}/health` · `GET .../ratings` (quality/tier) · `GET .../wallet/balance` · `GET .../business/profile`.

Response envelope is usually `{"status":"success"|"error", ...}` for portal APIs; **messaging v3 returns Meta-style** `{ messages:[{id}], contacts:[...] }`.

## 6. Sending messages

### 6a. Session message (v3, Meta-native shape) — 24h window only
`POST /partner/app/{appId}/v3/message`, `Content-Type: application/json`:
```json
{
  "messaging_product": "whatsapp",
  "recipient_type": "individual",
  "to": "9178XXXXXXXX",
  "type": "text",
  "text": { "body": "Hello", "preview_url": true }
}
```
- `to` = digits, country-code prefixed, **no `+`**. Reuse `send-whatsapp.js` phone canonicalization (`COUNTRY_DIAL_CODES`) — a bare 10-digit number is misrouted.
- Success → `{ "messages":[{"id":"<GS_MSG_ID>"}], ... }`. Persist that id as the provider message id (analogous to `metaMessageId`).
- Reply/quote a prior message with `"context": { "message_id": "<id>" }`.
- `400 "Callback Billing must be enabled for this API"` → the app isn't enabled for callback billing.

### 6b. Template message (outside 24h window)
`POST /partner/app/{appId}/template/msg`, `Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded`:
```
source=91XXXXXXXXXX            # business number, country-code prefixed
src.name=<APP_NAME>
destination=91XXXXXXXXXX       # customer number
template={"id":"<TEMPLATE_ID>","params":["v1","v2"]}
channel=whatsapp
```
- `template.params` is an **ordered array** matching `{{1}}, {{2}}...`. Count MUST match the approved template exactly (mismatch = failure; same class of bug as the MSG91 variable-count pitfall).
- Media/carousel headers go in the `message` field; quick-reply postbacks via `postbackTexts=[{"index":0,"text":"..."}]`.
- Success → `{ "status":"submitted", "messageId":"..." }`. Final delivery arrives via webhook callback.

## 7. Webhooks (inbound messages + status)

Set per-app with `POST /partner/app/{appId}/subscription` (form-urlencoded), rate limit **5/60s/app**:
```
modes=ALL           # or comma set: MESSAGE,SENT,DELIVERED,READ,FAILED,TEMPLATE,ACCOUNT,...
tag=<unique-name>   # unique & mandatory per app
url=https://<host>/api/gupshup/webhook
version=3           # use v3
meta={"headers":{"Authorization":"Bearer <shared-secret>"}}   # sent back as request headers → verify these
```

**Subscription modes:** `MESSAGE` (incoming, non-flow), `ALL` (all incoming), `SENT`/`DELIVERED`/`READ`/`FAILED` (status), `TEMPLATE`, `ACCOUNT`, `BILLING`, `FLOWS_MESSAGE`, `PAYMENTS`, `OTHERS`, `COEXISTENCE`.

**Webhook endpoint rules (non-negotiable):**
- Respond **HTTP 2xx with an empty body**, within **10s** (target < 100ms, acceptable 500–1000ms). Slow/failed ack → Gupshup retries.
- **Process asynchronously**: enqueue the payload (job/queue) and ack immediately. Never do DB-heavy work before responding.
- Must be **publicly reachable**, accept the `User-Agent` header, and handle the `sandbox-start` event.
- **Verify authenticity**: check the custom header you set via `meta`, AND allowlist Gupshup IPs (§8). Do not trust the payload blind.
- Status names: `sent`, `delivered`, `read`, `failed` (includes reason), `deleted`, `warning`. Map to the existing `WhatsAppMessage`/`WhatsAppMessageLog` status enum.

**Template lifecycle events (mandatory — Meta approval is async):**
- Legacy shape (`version=2` or default): `{ app, type: "template-event", payload: { id, elementName, languageCode, status, rejectedReason, type?: "status-update"|"category-update"|"quality-update" } }`. Statuses: `approved`, `rejected`, `paused`, `deleted`, `disabled`, `in_appeal`.
- v3 passthrough: `{ object: "whatsapp_business_account", entry: [{ changes: [{ field: "message_template_status_update", value: { event, message_template_id, message_template_name, message_template_language, reason } }] }] }`. Also handles `message_template_quality_update`, `template_category_update`, `message_template_category_update`.
- Our handler in `backend/routes/gupshup-webhook.js` (`applyTemplateEvent`) matches by `gupshupTemplateId`/`metaTemplateId`, then by `(businessId, elementName, languageCode)` when the id is unknown. Updates the local `WhatsAppTemplate` row (status / rejectionReason / approvedAt / previousCategory / detectedCorrectCategory / qualityScore). Without this handler tenant templates stay `pending` forever even after Meta approves — that is a common tenant-facing bug; always keep template-event handling wired.

